408. corresponding in translation to the English verbal noun in -c'ng, Latin has two forms, the geruud and the ynundtcc. The gerund is an active verbal and corresponds closely to the English verbal noun. It may in some uses govern an object just as the English verbcl noun does, but almost never in Caesar. So, ior the present, never use a geruud with a direct object. Examples: bellandi cupidi (234), desirous officinam paratus ad pro- ficiscendum, ready for cetuna oui. But in ready for prohinc him the gerundivo, not the gerund, must be used. The gerund has no nominative or vocative.
